title: Two parallel lines cut by a transversal

description.text: Students will practice using angle relationships given two parallel lines cut by a transversal. The focus of the questions range from numerical application to utilizing algebraic skills. Students will identify angles like alternate interior, alternate exterior, corresponding, and consecutive interior angles.

Two lines cut by a transversal

I created two parallel lines first. I then created a third line and rotated it so it cut through the two parallel lines on an angle. I placed numbers 1-8 in each angle (each intersection) and made sure they were attached to the lines. The lines should be high enough so they don't break easily as students use them. I also created terms, such as (2x-10) and (86+x) on flat rectangles that students can place in the angles depending on what the question is asking.
CCSS

Hand out the 3D objects to the class. Explain to students that they will use these objects to enhance their understanding of two parallel lines cut by a transversal. They will place the different terms in specific angles depending on the questions. Students will complete the worksheet attached.
Work sheet, attached

• identify angles
  • discover relationship
20-30 minutes

For this lesson, students should have an understanding of angles like alternate interior, alternate exterior, corresponding, and consecutive interior angles. This lesson builds upon students' knowledge of angles by having them use what they've learned to answer questions.

title: DiamondMind V2 - Modified Z Stop Assembly

description.text:
This is a modified Z Stop for a DiamondMind V2 3D Printer.
Created to allow Z-Stop adjustments simply by turning a knob. The package includes main bracket, stopper and adjustment knob.
To complete the modification you will need a 100mm M8 bolt, nut, nylock nut and a small screw. Updated with v1.2. I reprinted in black and found the fit differed from the print using white PLA. Try v1.2 if you had vertical play in the adjustment bolt.

After you print the 3 pieces (main bracket, knob and stopper), remove the existing bolt and wing nuts assembly.  
Fitting the nut/nylock into the new bracket is fiddly but they do fit, and can be pressed into place with long nose pliers.  Putting the rounded end of the nylock in the hole 1st makes it easier to fit.  The standard nut goes in the opposite hole.  
The bracket should slide onto/into the Z Stop black plastic frame on the printer.  Centre the holes and and screw the bolt through so it extends all the way through the bracket.  Once you have it looking and feeling right, use the small screw to fix end of bracket in place (stops it moving with you wind the knob).  
Fit the knob and the end stop and you're done.  The best thing it, you can easily go back to stock if desired.  
Now it's very easy to make z stop adjustments...  
Files include Sketchup, STL file and G-Code

description.text: I designed and printed all of the parts for our Enclosure for the MakerGear M2

Yes, you read correctly, the screen of an IPad, not the whole tablet itself!

I needed a small secondary monitor for my workstation. I was going to get a cheap LCD screen but a friend of mine suggested that I build a monitor from an IPad screen. I got interested and started to find more information about the process. 2048x1536 resolution in a 9.7" size?!

These are two main components that you need; The screen itself and an adapter board that sits between the computer and the screen. As the screen is already signal compatible with the Displayport standard, you can hook it up to a Mac or PC by using an adapter board that makes all the necessary connector hookups and provide power for the backlight on the screen.

Here are the links to the items that I bought for the project:
IPad 3 screen:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/For-Apple-iPad-3-iPad-4-3rd-4th-Gen-4G-LCD-Screen-Display-Replacement-Part-New/361324323712

Adapter board made by Abusemark:
http://abusemark.com/store/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=3&products_id=47

16 x m3 10-12 mm bolts. I used hex socket ones.
16 x m3 lock nuts. Or regular ones if you like, doesn't matter that much.
4 x m3 10 mm bolts, to mount the adapter cover. I used nylon ones, easier to cut to size.
4 x m3 10 mm bolts, flat head for the VESA mount
4 x m4 10 mm bolts, for mounting the arm to the VESA mount

After that it was just a matter of designing the case and the mount for the screen. I used the Fusion 360 to sketch out the case and one additional piece for mounting it by using the VESA standard 50mm hole spacing.

This is the mounting arm that I printed:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2276448

The part needed to adjust the angle is included with my project. I think I'll make a remix too for that part alone and point it towards jeffreyk's arm project.

And finally here is a video that I made from the steps of this project:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FPF-3X7V4U4

I have also provided a basic info sheet to help, which contains the eye and mouth decals. If you print on A4 paper size they should be the right size to stick onto the model when printed at 1:1 scale (obviously depends on your 2D printer settings but it's a good starting point).

All parts printed Printed Parts

After printing the parts there isn't really and clean up, it's designed so all parts print flat on the print bed and there is barely any overhang.

Glue the arms, neck, legs and waist parts together flat edge to flat edge.

There is a 0.1mm gap between parts so depending on the accuracy of your 3D printer the parts might need a little carving down to slot into each other. They need to be a tight fit so you can pose him.

Obviously if painting this will add additional layers you would need to remove before assembling again.

It's a g-g-g-ghost Roberto! Finishing

My model was painted with 3-4 coats of acrylic paints, then I 2D printed the eyes and mouth decals on vinyl printer paper and stuck them on.

Check the info sheet in the main images which has those decals and other information on there.

description.text: This is a fishing rod handle. It is portable, easy to use, and requires little time to setup. To setup your fishing rod handle you slide your reel into the bottom piece of the handle and then screw on the top piece of the handle. Next, you insert your rod into the hole on top of the handle, for this, you may need to drill out the hole a little bit. For drilling out the hole I recommend you to have the drill set in reverse, having your drill in reverse doesn't rip out the layers of the handle. For the rod, I used the top of a two part rod I bought at Walmart and for the reel, I used the reel from the same rod I bought from Walmart. The rod or reel doesn't really matter it just matters if your rod is the male end of the rod. Almost any two part rod should work.

description.text:
These STL files are designed to equip my Sculptris Dummies. You won't be able to import these files into Sculptris, though once you get your character posed, you can align these parts in any model staging platform (MakerBot Deskto, Blender, Meshmixer, or 3D Builder are all good choices). All of these parts are also available in Andrew Stockton's awesome Desktop Hero project as well (which is quite a bit easier than adjusting all the parts by hand). All of these weapons have been scaled to 28mm/Heroic scale, so they should be ready for any kind of miniature conversion if you want to print them separately.

If you make anything with these (including through Desktop Hero), let me know and post a link here in the comments section (and certainly post a remix when you have something printable). I'd love to see what you come up with!

You can find an expanding collection of compatible parts here.

We've set up a Patreon page for anyone who's interested in helping to fund us so we can keep making free and open sourced games like Pocket-Tactics, Wayfarer Tactics. and others, not to mention the growing catalog of gaming miniatures that you can use for whatever you want! (Psst... we take requests and commissions...)

Enjoy!

title: Solar Finder for hot shoe on camera for solar and eclipse photos

description.text:
If you plan on taking photos of the sun, especially during the eclipse of the sun, you don't want to look through the viewfinder to locate the sun and burn your eyes out. So you need a "solar finder". There are lots of these for telescopes, but this one fits in the hot shoe (where the flash goes) on your camera. The sun shines through a small hole in the front and makes a dot on the angled part. When the sun shines in the center of the circle, then the camera is pointed at the sun properly. You need to use a solar filter (not part of this print.. you can buy them from astronomy supply stores) on the front of the camera so you don't burn out your camera or worse, start a fire in it. Then you can try various exposure settings until you get a good photo. This is for use when the sun is not totally eclipsed. For totality, you would slip off the solar filter in front and hopefully you would have already pointed the camera in the proper direction. Only during totality, you can use the viewfinder.

Anyway, to make this, I printed using ABS with a 0.35mm nozzle, using 0.1mm layer thickness. After printing, cut out a piece of white 3x5 card to glue on the angled part. Then push a pin through the back of the angled part's hole to locate the correct point on the card and draw a circle there. You might want to test it first outside with the sun (before drawing the circle) in case you had any warping problems printing this thing. You might have to use a fingernail file or 1 to 3 layer folded 120 grit sandpaper to sand off any excess ABS if it doesn't quite fit your hot shoe (especially for the slots). Have fun taking solar photos with your camera!

description.text:
It can be hard to talk about 3D printing to anyone who isn't familiar with the technology. Having something on your person that can help explain the whole printing process is helpful, as well as being a neat conversation piece. Sure, pens are super cheap and more or less utilitarian, but a 3D printed pen (let alone bolt action) is pretty neat in my opinion. Used it on my exams!

Feel free to print in whatever color plastic you want that matches your ink color! Just be sure to use filament with good layer adhesion (probably won't matter for the majority of people).

Side note the small hole in the body of the pen near the tip is to monitor how much ink the cartridge has. Once you no longer see ink through the hole, it's time to change your cartridge.

Assembly

Parts needed:
M2 6mm Bolt and Nut
This was designed to use a Pilot G-2 0.5 pen, but G-2 0.7 will probably work too.

Unscrew your G-2 pen and take out the ink cartridge and spring. On your printed housing, you may want to take a file to make sure the ink cartridge doesn't get stuck in the initial hole at the bottom. Also try to clean out the bolt slot such that the M2 bolt can actually slide freely without hitting the sides.
Insert the spring, ink cartridge, and plunger cylinder into the pen body, with the build plate side of the plunger going in first. Make sure to align the hole in the plunger with the bolt slot in the pen
Screw the M2 nut onto the bolt, then screw both into the hole in the plunger through the bolt slot. You may need to push the plunger into the pen a little bit.
Push the end cap onto the end of your pen. It should just be a friction fit, but if you want to, use super glue to permanently attach it. This will make it so you have no way of changing the ink cartridge once your ink depletes.
I sanded my pen, but this is totally optional. I used 220 and 320 grit.

Enjoy your new-fangled writing utensil!

description.text:
A simple but very effective parameterized box divider (now with optional sidewalls!), intended for lasercutting but probably printable as well (I haven't tried).  Simply measure the interior diameter of your (rectangular) box, choose the number of divisions and the material thickness, and go.  Very useful for making small compartments inside old cigar boxes and such.  
By default, the "flat" version should let you produce a DXF file in OpenScad, which is what you want for the lasercutter, but the "assembled" version might be useful for some folks who want to print them (and just for seeing how it should come out).   You may have to download to get the DXF (set flat_to_assembled to "flat", and in OpenScad, "Design->Compile and Render (CGAL)", then "Design->Export to DXF").  
I have added sidewalls since my first production test, but the new version has NOT been tested.
The dividers shown were laser-cut in 3mm MDF and placed in a 1970s-era cigar box.

Mounted to the eye is a 10mm blue LED. The head itself is attached to a servo horn and mounted to a micro servo. The head can freely rotate while the eye blink randomly. Surrounding the body are 5mm blue LEDs that illuminate the various surface details.

The random motion of the servo and eye blinks give the illusion of the robot "searching". It's appears quite organic and live like, adding much more dimension to this replica.

Check out the full documentation for this project to build your own. https://learn.adafruit.com/guardian-robot-zelda-botw/

The Fusion 360 source file contains editable solids and micro servo component.

title: Printrbot Simple Wide Foot Print Foot Pegs

description.text:
The original feet for https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:593072 were too big to insert in the bracket, because I did not have flexible filament. Originals probably fit snug, when printed with different filament.

Someone mentioned https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:280489 these scaled at 130%, however they were too big. Bottoms are 1"; I tried to use felt pads, but they slide to much.

So I created these and made them from stock PLA, they are 3/4" or 20mm & they fit perfect & snapped into place. I added some rubber pads from Home Depot, and the now the printer does not shift around or move, and it is quietier.

Shout out to Thorped for the design on the foot bar, it is very durable and the best I have seen yet. Snaps into place and widens the stance. Highly recommend you print it, try all of the pegs and find what works best for you.

*** Update... I did remix the the pegs and created a small void for a .5" pad, this is the one I have been using on 3 Simple Metals for the past 6 months. You can buy sticky rubber .5" pads for a few dollars at Home Depot. They work better because the rubber pad stays in place. I printed them with a 15% support (easier to remove). The pad fits snug, which is good and makes it to where the machine is not only quiet but doesn't vibrate on the table.
